{
  "answer": "**In chapter 9 of *Traité de Législation Vol. I*, Charles Comte illustrates the potential discordance between (narrow) morality/law and broader human utility through historical and hypothetical examples of actions beneficial at a national level but harmful overall.**[^1]\n\nHe describes how a general's treason might initially draw hatred only to himself, but if rewarded by the enemy, hatred spreads to the beneficiaries. Similarly, a minister who makes his nation great by scourging others may die honored, but the resulting hatred endures and targets the nation, as \"nations do not die.\" He cites **the specific case of Rome**: nations oppressed by Rome \"reacted against the Roman people, and made them pay for the triumphs they had decreed to their generals.\"[^2]\n\nThis shows how national laws and morality (e.g., rewarding conquerors) can conflict with universal morality, as such actions produce more hatred/evil than good relative to the \"entire human race,\" ultimately undermining the favoring society.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, ch. 9 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/09-de-la-doctrine-qui-fonde-la-morale-et-la-legislati/translation/#p-5ad19d).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, ch. 9 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/09-de-la-doctrine-qui-fonde-la-morale-et-la-legislati/translation/#p-ec812d).\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, ch. 9 [full chapter](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/09-de-la-doctrine-qui-fonde-la-morale-et-la-legislati/translation/).",
